##############################################

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "contextFraction.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("Numeric");

$a = random(2,10,1);
$b = $a;
$b = random(2,10,1) while($b==$a);

$numerator = Compute("$b-$a");
$denominator = Compute("$a*$b");

Context("LimitedFraction");
Context()->flags->set(showMixedNumbers=>0, requireProperFractions=>1);
$ans = Fraction("$numerator/($denominator)");

##############################################
TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML
Here is an expression with negative exponents.

    [`
        [$a]^{-1}-[$b]^{-1}=
     `][____________]{$ans}

Evaluate the expression; in other words, write the answer 
without using exponents. Hint: you will need to _subtract_ fractions for this problem.

END_PGML

#dump out numerator and denominator for display purposes

@answ = $ans->value;
$ansNum = $answ[0];
$ansDen = $answ[1];

if ($ans<0) {
   $ansNum = -$ansNum;
   $output = "-\frac{$ansNum}{$ansDen}";
}
else {
   $output = "\frac{$ansNum}{$ansDen}";
}

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

We evaluate the expression by remembering that [`x^{-n}`] is the same thing as [``\frac{1}{x^n}``] for any non-zero, real value of [`x`]. Once we have rewritten each term, the problem is a simple fraction problem.

    [``
      \begin{aligned}
            [$a]^{-1}-[$b]^{-1} & = \frac{1}{[$a]}-\frac{1}{[$b]}\\
                                & = \frac{1}{[$a]}\cdot\frac{[$b]}{[$b]}-\frac{1}{[$b]}\cdot\frac{[$a]}{[$a]}\\
                               & = \frac{[$b]-[$a]}[$denominator]\\
                             & = \displaystyle[$output] \\
                             &
      \end{aligned}
    ``]


END_PGML_SOLUTION
##############################################


ENDDOCUMENT();
